In English, /b/ or less technically the "b" sound is bi-labial meaning that it uses both the bottom and the top lip whereas /f/ is labio-dental using the lip and the bottom teeth. Neither labio-dental plosives which sounds like /b/ and /p/ nor the bi-labial fricative which sounds like /v/ and /f/ appear in English. This may lead to the brain attaching to a sound that appears in English: [fa] eg father.
